Abstract: International trade intermediaries, such as export management companies, have long existed in the United States. Many studies and reports have provided &ldquo;snapshots&rdquo; of their activities and roles over time. Their evolution, however, has hardly been researched&mdash;mainly for lack of an appropriate dynamic model. This paper integrates various conceptual frameworks and theories to develop a useful mode of the evolution of the U.S. international trade intermediary in the 1980s.&copy; 1990 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1990) 21, 133&ndash;153
